{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"20baa970-6f10-405d-9ff1-d0241367d3ff","content":"The best approach is **`dotnet-trace`** — it's lightweight and works well in containers:\n\n```bash\n# 1. Install the tool inside the pod\ndotnet tool install -g dotnet-trace\n\n# 2. Find your app's PID\ndotnet-trace ps\n\n# 3. Collect a CPU trace (default profile is cpu-sampling)\ndotnet-trace collect -p <PID> --duration 00:00:30\n```\n\nThis produces a `.nettrace` file you can analyze in **Visual Studio**, **PerfView**, or [Speedscope](https://www.speedscope.app).\n\n**Tips:**\n- If `dotnet tool` isn't available, download the standalone binary:\n  ```bash\n  curl -sSL https://aka.ms/dotnet-trace/linux-x64 -o dotnet-trace\n  chmod +x dotnet-trace\n  ```\n- For flame-graph-style analysis, convert to `.speedscope.json`:\n  ```bash\n  dotnet-trace convert trace.nettrace --format Speedscope\n  ```\n- For deeper OS-level analysis (GC, JIT, kernel events), use **`dotnet-counters`** first to narrow down, then **`perfcollect`** if you need perf + LTTng traces.\n- Copy the trace out with:\n  ```bash\n  kubectl cp <pod>:/path/to/trace.nettrace ./trace.nettrace\n  ```","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"a573c3b0-c8f0-4ef0-8ca0-de6d1da9b1be","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking for guidance on collecting a CPU trace from a .NET 8 app running in a Kubernetes pod on Linux. This is a diagnostic/troubleshooting question, not a code change request. I'll provide a concise answer based on my knowledge.","outputTokens":422,"requestId":"4187:2AE020:70583A4:7C2142C:69F15F08"},"id":"fe81baa9-13fc-43de-b4d6-823fe5f550fc","timestamp":"2026-04-29T01:29:54.622Z","parentId":"23ecd41e-1246-4cbf-85f1-8242925aa354"}
